      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t particularly care either way, but I think you may want to think through the cost of what that implies.  It\u0027s likely more expensive to write this as\n\n   select(isNaN(x), 0, x)\n\nthan as\n\n   select(is_not_NaN(x), x, 0)\n\nSpecial-casing select(c, 0, x) into (~c)\u0026x is not an optimization.  That replaces one select instruction with 3 inputs (c,0,x) with two instructions with 3 inputs (c and x, and in your impl ~0), and now it also needs a temporary register to hold ~c.  In all the other select special cases we strictly reduce the number of instructions or number of inputs, but the transformation of c?0:x ~~\u003e (~c)\u0026x increases the number of instructions and does not change the number of inputs, making things I suspect strictly worse.",
      "parentUuid": "55105f46_d2ca3c2d",
